# Documented below are the steps followed to solve the Display 2: error when attempting to launch 'Start SOS'
# Three of the four projectors are connected via HDMI to DVI adapters to the Quadro M4000. 
# The primary consistent error when initializing Display 2: manually via the command 'sudo /usr/bin/X :2 vt3 -sharevts -config xorg-projectors-twinview.conf -noreset -dpms -s 0 &'
  # NVIDIA(GPU-0): Failed to acquire modesetting permission.
  # NVIDIA(GPU-1): Failed to acquire modesetting permission.
  
1. Udev Seat Separation (/etc/udev/rules.d/61-gdm.rules)
Uncommented the two pre-existing rules that were already written but disabled:
SUBSYSTEM=="drm", KERNEL=="card2", TAG+="seat", ENV{ID_SEAT}="seat0"
SUBSYSTEM=="drm", KERNEL=="card1", TAG+="seat", ENV{ID_SEAT}="seat1"
This was the core fix — it freed the Quadro M4000 (card1) from the main X session's grip, allowing the SOS X server to acquire modesetting permission on display :2.

2. Projector Config (/etc/X11/xorg-projectors-twinview.conf)
Stripped out the forced display options that were causing X to fail even once the Quadro was free:

Removed ConnectedMonitor, metamodes, and CustomEDID lines
Corrected BusID to PCI:3:0:0 (Quadro M4000)
Simplified to let the driver auto-detect connected displays

3. GDM Multi-Seat (/etc/gdm3/custom.conf)
Added MultiSeat=false under [daemon] to prevent GDM from hijacking seat1 and disrupting the main session.
Bonus Fix — Input Devices (/etc/X11/xorg.conf)
Replaced the broken evdev driver with libinput for keyboard and mouse, restoring main display interactivity.